<div class="info-panel hidden stagger-3">
<div class="card" style="margin-bottom:20px;">
<p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--cyan);font-family:monospace;letter-spacing:0.1em;margin-bottom:12px;">WHAT IS A GRAIN?</p>
<p>A grain is a micro-segment of audio, typically <strong>1–100 milliseconds</strong> long — shorter than any musical note, longer than a single cycle of a waveform. At this scale, sound becomes something else entirely.</p>
<p>Granular synthesis atomizes any sound into hundreds or thousands of grains, then reassembles them with independent control over grain size, density, pitch randomization, and position scatter. Each dot in the cloud is one grain.</p>
</div>
<div class="card" style="margin-bottom:20px;">
<p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--cyan);font-family:monospace;letter-spacing:0.1em;margin-bottom:12px;">SIZE DETERMINES IDENTITY</p>
<p><strong>Small grains (&lt; 50ms):</strong> pure texture, no pitch identity — the source becomes unrecognizable, a shimmer or cloud.</p>
<p><strong>Medium grains (50–200ms):</strong> pitched fragments, the source is vaguely recognizable — vowel shapes, string attacks, cymbal character.</p>
<p><strong>Large grains (&gt; 200ms):</strong> near-original sound — you can hear the instrument, the room, the breath.</p>
</div>
<div class="card">
<p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--cyan);font-family:monospace;letter-spacing:0.1em;margin-bottom:12px;">GABOR'S QUANTA</p>
<p>The technique was theorized by physicist <strong>Denis Gabor</strong> in 1946 as <em>acoustic quanta</em> — applying Heisenberg's uncertainty principle to sound. Pitch and time cannot both be precisely known at the microsound scale. A shorter grain has less pitch identity; a longer grain has less temporal precision.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</section>
