<!-- SECTION 05: MICROSOUND TIMELINE -->
<section data-nav="05" id="timeline" style="background:linear-gradient(to bottom,var(--black),rgba(6,182,212,0.03),var(--black));">
<div class="section-inner">
<div class="section-header hidden stagger-1">
<span class="section-num">05 — MICROSOUND TIMELINE</span>
<h2>70 YEARS OF GRAIN</h2>
<p class="thesis">From acoustic quanta theory to Eurorack modules.</p>
</div>
<div class="timeline-scroll hidden stagger-2">
<div class="timeline-inner">
<div class="timeline-line"></div>
<div class="timeline-event">
<div class="timeline-date">1946</div>
<div class="timeline-title">Denis Gabor — "Theory of Communication"</div>
<div class="timeline-desc">Proposed acoustic quanta, applying Heisenberg's uncertainty principle to audio. Established that pitch and time precision are mutually exclusive at small scales — the theoretical foundation of all granular synthesis.</div>
</div>
<div class="timeline-event">
<div class="timeline-date">1959</div>
<div class="timeline-title">Iannis Xenakis — "Analogique A+B"</div>
<div class="timeline-desc">First granular synthesis composition, realized by hand-splicing magnetic tape into tiny fragments and reassembling them according to stochastic probability scores. An impossible human labor that took months to complete.</div>
</div>
<div class="timeline-event">
<div class="timeline-date">1974</div>
<div class="timeline-title">Gottfried Michael Koenig — "Project 1"</div>
<div class="timeline-desc">Computer-aided stochastic composition at the Institute of Sonology, Utrecht. Early formalization of algorithmic processes for granular-adjacent sound design, helping bridge Xenakis's theory and digital practice.</div>
</div>
<div class="timeline-event">
<div class="timeline-date">1985</div>
<div class="timeline-title">Barry Truax — "Riverrun"</div>
<div class="timeline-desc">First real-time granular synthesis on a computer (DMX-1000 signal processor). The piece transforms water sounds into vast river textures using granular time-stretching — a landmark in electroacoustic music.</div>
</div>
<div class="timeline-event">
<div class="timeline-date">1988</div>
<div class="timeline-title">Curtis Roads — Formalization</div>
<div class="timeline-desc">Roads formalizes granular synthesis terminology in his writings, later consolidated in <em>The Computer Music Tutorial</em> (1996) and <em>Microsound</em> (2001). His taxonomy — synchronous, asynchronous, pitch-synchronous — defines the field.</div>
</div>
<div class="timeline-event">
<div class="timeline-date">1995</div>
<div class="timeline-title">Autechre — "Garbage" (Anvil Vapre EP)</div>
<div class="timeline-desc">Granular rhythm as electronic music aesthetic. Autechre begin applying granular processing to percussion, creating rhythmic grain clouds that dissolve the boundary between beat and texture — a defining IDM move.</div>
</div>
<div class="timeline-event">
<div class="timeline-date">2002</div>
<div class="timeline-title">William Basinski — "Disintegration Loops"</div>
<div class="timeline-desc">Accidental granular dissolution: playing deteriorating 1980s tape loops while recording the process of their physical destruction. The magnetic oxide flaking from the tape became the instrument. Released on September 13, 2001.</div>
</div>
<div class="timeline-event">
<div class="timeline-date">2010</div>
<div class="timeline-title">Ableton Live 8 — Mainstream DAW</div>
<div class="timeline-desc">Granular capabilities reach mainstream DAW users via third-party instruments and later native tools. Producers in pop, electronic, and film scoring gain access to granular time-stretching in their everyday workflow.</div>
</div>
<div class="timeline-event">
<div class="timeline-date">2018</div>
<div class="timeline-title">Mutable Instruments Clouds</div>
<div class="timeline-desc">Granular synthesis as Eurorack hardware module — discontinued in 2017 due to ubiquity, but remains the most-cloned module in the modular synthesis world. Brought real-time granular manipulation to hardware performance contexts.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</section>
<!-- SECTION 06: ARTISTS -->
<section data-nav="06" id="artists">
<div class="section-inner">
<div class="section-header hidden stagger-1">
<span class="section-num">06 — ARTISTS</span>
<h2>WHO WORKED WITH THE GRAIN</h2>
<p class="thesis">Eight composers who dissolved sound into particles.</p>
</div>
<div class="artist-grid hidden stagger-2">
<div class="artist-card">
<p class="artist-name">Iannis Xenakis</p>
<p class="artist-years">1922–2001 // FORMALIZED MUSIC</p>
<p class="artist-desc">Stochastic composition pioneer. Applied Markov chains, Poisson distributions, and Brownian motion to determine every parameter of a composition. His <em>Analogique A+B</em> (1959) was the first granular piece, assembled by hand from tape fragments.</p>
</div>
<div class="artist-card">
<p class="artist-name">Curtis Roads</p>
<p class="artist-years">b. 1951 // THE COMPUTER MUSIC TUTORIAL</p>
<p class="artist-desc">Coined the term <em>microsound</em>. Defined granular synthesis as a formal discipline in his landmark 2001 book. His own compositions — <em>Half-Life</em>, <em>Sculptor</em> — use granular clouds as primary compositional material.</p>
</div>
<div class="artist-card">
<p class="artist-name">Barry Truax</p>
<p class="artist-years">b. 1947 // RIVERRUN (1985)</p>
<p class="artist-desc">Created the first real-time granular synthesis piece on computer. Pioneered granular time-stretching and acoustic ecology approaches, using environmental sounds as source material for electroacoustic works.</p>
</div>
<div class="artist-card">
<p class="artist-name">William Basinski</p>
<p class="artist-years">b. 1958 // DISINTEGRATION LOOPS</p>
<p class="artist-desc">Accidental granular artist. Playing deteriorating tape loops while recording their dissolution — the magnetic oxide flakes from the tape as it runs, each pass removing a little more. Released September 13, 2001, as the World Trade Center burned.</p>
</div>
<div class="artist-card">
<p class="artist-name">Tim Hecker</p>
<p class="artist-years">b. 1974 // RAVEDEATH 1972</p>
<p class="artist-desc">Granular guitar processing creates dense spectral shimmer fields. Albums like <em>Ravedeath 1972</em> (2011) and <em>Harmony in Ultraviolet</em> (2006) apply granular techniques to organ and guitar, transforming tonal sources into immersive fog.</p>
</div>
<div class="artist-card">
<p class="artist-name">Fennesz</p>
<p class="artist-years">b. 1962 // ENDLESS SUMMER (2001)</p>
<p class="artist-desc">Classical guitar recordings granularized into shimmering, droning ambient textures. <em>Endless Summer</em> processes the Beach Boys' harmonic language through laptop granular tools, creating something at once nostalgic and completely alien.</p>
</div>
<div class="artist-card">
<p class="artist-name">Kim Cascone</p>
<p class="artist-years">b. 1955 // POST-DIGITAL AESTHETICS</p>
<p class="artist-desc">Granular and glitch synthesis as critique of digital perfection. Coined the term <em>post-digital</em> in his influential 2000 essay. Former director of multimedia at Lucasfilm; now creates work from the sonic artifacts of computational failure.</p>
</div>
<div class="artist-card">
<p class="artist-name">Autechre</p>
<p class="artist-years">EST. 1987 // CONFIELD / UNTILTED</p>
<p class="artist-desc">Granular rhythm programming using Max/MSP. Grain clouds as percussion texture throughout <em>Confield</em> (2001) and <em>Untilted</em> (2005). Their approach treats rhythm as a probability space rather than a grid — grains activate according to conditional logic.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</section>
<!-- SECTION 07: GLOSSARY -->
<section data-nav="07" id="glossary" style="background:linear-gradient(to bottom,var(--black),rgba(168,85,247,0.03),var(--black));">
<div class="section-inner">
<div class="section-header hidden stagger-1">
<span class="section-num">07 — GLOSSARY</span>
<h2>20 TERMS</h2>
<p class="thesis">The vocabulary of microsound.</p>
</div>
<div class="glossary-grid hidden stagger-2">
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Grain</span><p class="gloss-def">A micro-segment of audio, typically 1–100ms. The fundamental unit of granular synthesis — a quantum of sound.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Grain Cloud</span><p class="gloss-def">The aggregate texture produced by many overlapping grains. The cloud is the composition; no single grain is audible in isolation.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Grain Size</span><p class="gloss-def">Duration of each grain in milliseconds. Determines whether the source is recognizable — small grains produce texture, large grains preserve identity.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Grain Density</span><p class="gloss-def">Number of grains triggered per second. High density produces continuous texture; low density creates sparse, isolated sonic events.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Scatter</span><p class="gloss-def">Randomization of grain position within the source file. High scatter reads from random points; low scatter reads linearly, preserving the original sequence.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Pitch Randomization</span><p class="gloss-def">Random transposition of individual grains, measured in semitones. Spreads the cloud vertically — from unison to wide chromatic smear.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Position</span><p class="gloss-def">The read-head location within the source file, from 0.0 (start) to 1.0 (end). Can be automated to create granular scrubbing through a recording.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Microsound</span><p class="gloss-def">Curtis Roads's term for sound at the sub-note time scale (1ms–500ms). The domain in which individual grains exist and human pitch/rhythm perception breaks down.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Stochastic</span><p class="gloss-def">Random processes governed by probability distributions. Xenakis's key contribution: replacing compositional decisions with statistical functions that generate controlled randomness.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Probability Distribution</span><p class="gloss-def">A mathematical function describing the likelihood of each possible value. Gaussian (bell curve), uniform, and exponential distributions all produce different grain cloud characters.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Time-Stretching</span><p class="gloss-def">Changing the duration of audio without affecting pitch. Granular time-stretch achieves this by repeating or omitting grains — the most artifact-free method at extreme ratios.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Phase Vocoder</span><p class="gloss-def">An FFT-based time-stretch method that maintains phase coherence between frequency bins. Smoother than granular but prone to characteristic "phasiness" on transient-rich sources.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Acoustic Quanta</span><p class="gloss-def">Gabor's 1946 term for the elementary units of acoustic information, analogous to photons in light. Each quantum has a location in time and frequency — but not both with arbitrary precision.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Gabor Atom</span><p class="gloss-def">A Gaussian-windowed sinusoid — the mathematically optimal grain shape for representing sound. Minimizes the time-frequency uncertainty product as defined by the Heisenberg limit.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Dissolution</span><p class="gloss-def">The gradual breakdown of granular parameters — increasing scatter, randomizing size, reducing density — until the source is unrecognizable. Basinski's tapes dissolved literally; granular synthesis can simulate this entropy.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Freeze Effect</span><p class="gloss-def">Setting position scatter to maximum and position automation to zero, creating a static cloud from a single moment in the source audio. A sonic photograph — an instant held forever in granular suspension.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Granulation</span><p class="gloss-def">The process of breaking audio into grains. All granular synthesis begins with granulation of a source — live input, recorded sample, or synthesized waveform.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Texture</span><p class="gloss-def">In granular synthesis, texture refers to a sonic mass without clear pitch or rhythmic identity — the emergent quality of thousands of micro-events heard as a single homogeneous sound.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Murmuration</span><p class="gloss-def">The visual analog of granular synthesis: a flock of starlings moving as a unified cloud. Each bird follows simple rules; the group produces complex, unpredictable, beautiful patterns.</p></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><span class="gloss-term">Async. Granular</span><p class="gloss-def">Asynchronous granular synthesis: grains are triggered at random intervals within a density range, rather than at fixed periodic intervals. Produces more organic, less mechanical cloud textures.</p></div>
</div>
</div>
</section>
